Lab 7 Part A¶

1. Data set creation¶

Firstly, I used vfmt to convert the picture to VisionX image file. Take one of the written character as an example.

vfmt -g if=c27.JPG of=c27.vx;

In [1]:
from PIL import Image
display(Image.open("./dataset/c27.gif"))

This command changes the image format to the VisionX format and changes it to greyscale.

Then, I used vpix to threshold images and changed them to bilevel images. I chose the threshold value as 75 after some testing. For this process, the pixel would be be 0 when exceeding the threshold. That setting can also give the image light foreground and dark background. The command and result is shown below.

vpix if=c27.vx th=75 hi=0 lo=255 of=c27t.vx

In [2]:
display(Image.open("./dataset/c27b.gif"))

After that, I wrote a program to find the edge of my hand written character. I checked whether a pixel is 255, and get the longer length as the size of a rectangle. After this step I pass the coordinate of left bottom point and the top right bottom of that rectangle and I cut the rest of the background using vclip.

boundary if=.c27t.vx | xargs vclip if=c27t.vx of=c27b.vx;

Then, I used command to rescale bounding box of c27b and then I used vimag to rescale the image to 20*20. The command and result is shown below.

vibbox if=c27b.vx -xy of=c27bb.vx;

vimag if=c27bb.vx s=20,20,1 of=c27s.vx;

In [3]:
display(Image.open("./dataset/c27s.gif"))

In this step, I wrote a program to find the COM of my character in size 2020 and reposition it in to 2828. My command and result is shown below.

size28 if=c27s.vx of=c27ss.vx;

In [4]:
display(Image.open("./dataset/c27ss.gif"))

Finally, I convert VisionX file to the .png file.

vxport if=c27ss.vx -png of=c27;

For my convenience, I wrote a script to process those pictures that I took from the paper and make my own dataset. The script is shown below.

In [ ]:
# !/bin/sh
#
for i in {0..59..1}
do
vfmt -g if=./dataset/c$i.JPG of=./dataset/c$i.vx;
vpix if=./dataset/c$i.vx th=75 hi=0 lo=255 of=./dataset/c$(printf "%dt" "$i").vx;
boundary if=./dataset/c$(printf "%dt" "$i").vx | xargs vclip if=./dataset/c$(printf "%dt" "$i").vx of=./dataset/c$(printf "%db" "$i").vx;
vibbox if=./dataset/c${i}b.vx -xy of=./dataset/c${i}bb.vx;
vimag if=./dataset/c${i}bb.vx s=20,20,1 of=./dataset/c${i}s.vx;
size28 if=./dataset/c${i}s.vx of=./dataset/c${i}ss.vx;
vxport if=./dataset/c${i}ss.vx -png of=./dataset/result/c${i};
done

#2.  read the NMIST dataset
memory = Memory(get_data_home())
@memory.cache()
def fetch_mnist():
    content = urlopen(
        'https://www.openml.org/data/download/52667/mnist_784.arff').read()
    data, meta = loadarff(io.StringIO(content.decode('utf8')))
    data = data.view([('pixels', '<f8', 784), ('class', '|S1')])
    return data['pixels'], data['class']
X, y = fetch_mnist()

#train and test classifier
# Turn up tolerance for faster convergence
clf = LogisticRegression(C=50. / 1000,
                         multi_class='multinomial',
                         penalty='l1', solver='saga', tol=0.1)
# Train the classifier
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

#Evaluate the classifier
sparsity = np.mean(clf.coef_ == 0) * 100
score = clf.score(X_test, y_test)
# print('Best C % .4f' % clf.C_)
print("Sparsity with L1 penalty: %.2f%%" % sparsity)
print("Test score with L1 penalty: %.4f" % score)

### Bonus 3: comfusion matrix visualization tool
## A more elegant preserntation for a confusion matrix

import itertools
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    #print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.tight_layout()

""" Custom datatset loader
    based on https://github.com/utkuozbulak/pytorch-custom-dataset-examples
"""
import pandas as pd
import imageio

class SimpleDataset():
    def __init__(self, data_path, csv_name, transform = None ):
        """
        Args:
            data_path (string): path to the folder where images and csv files are located
            csv_name (string): name of the csv lablel file
            transform: pytorch transforms for transforms and tensor conversion
        """
        # Set path
        self.data_path = data_path
        # Read the csv file
        self.data_info = pd.read_csv(data_path + csv_name, header=None)
        # First column contains the image paths
        self.image_arr = np.asarray(self.data_info.iloc[:, 0])
        # Second column is the labels
        self.label_arr = np.asarray(self.data_info.iloc[:, 1])
        # Calculate len
        self.data_len = len(self.data_info.index)
        
    def __getitem__(self, index):
        # Get image name from the pandas df
        single_image_name = self.image_arr[index]
        # Open image
        img_as_img = imageio.imread(self.data_path + single_image_name)
        
        # Get label(class) of the image based on the cropped pandas column
        single_image_label = self.label_arr[index]
        
        return (img_as_img, single_image_label)

    def __len__(self):
        return self.data_len

1. Evaluate the performance of the classifier described in the Lab tutorial for both the standard test dataset and also your own dataset.¶

The accuracy of the classifier for the test dataset is 90.25%. Although there are some error for this dataset, the overall result is good and the classifier works well for MNIST dataset. However, the accuracy of my own dataset is very low. Firstly, my own dataset is not large enough to let the classifier learn my writing style and recognize my hand-written character. Also, I think the logistic regression is too simple to have a very good result for this dataset.
